Missing Entry Point: I noticed TaskManager.java lacks a public static void main method. The physical entry point must live in a separate file like Main.java or App.java that instantiates this engine.Memory vs. Database Analytics: The getStatistics method doesn't run external database queries. It dynamically aggregates active file records in-memory using Java HashMap collections.

Exercise Part 2:

I ran an internal code search across the provided codebase to determine how to best integrate the new "Task Export to CSV" feature requested by the team lead.
Search Terms Used: save, storage, write, File, export, FileI/O
Existing Files Found: TaskManager.java (References to an external file called TaskStorage.java)

Initial Observations & Findings
Existing File Operations:
The codebase delegates all physical disk operations to TaskStorage. For example, storage.save() is triggered during updates to write the task state to the disk using the file path string variable storagePath.
Data Transformation:
The getStatistics() method shows that the application frequently uses Java Streams (.stream()) and lambda filters to loop through, reshape, and collect task objects in memory. This pattern is highly reusable for processing data before a file export.
Reusable Utilities:
storage.getAllTasks() returns a complete list of task records (List<Task>). This serves as the precise data payload needed for a CSV export loop.
